{"key":"processedPost-12430662","value":{"id":12430662,"first":12430093,"last":12430996,"when":1271859360,"utime":"04/21/10 05:16 PM","content":"If you squeeze <i>really hard</i>, a small stream should flow for only a second or two and then stop.&nbsp; There's a difference in squeezing strength between someone who works in an office and a construction worker.&nbsp; The descriptions given are to get you through the first few projects, after which time every&nbsp; grower realizes exactly how moist a substrate should be.<br />The fluffier a given substrate is, the more water will squeeze out.&nbsp; That's why with sawdust, I adjust so not one single drop comes out when squeezed as hard as I can.&nbsp; However, with coir, compost, manure, etc., adjust as mentioned in the first paragraph above and demonstrated on the <a href=\"http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Casing-Layer-Preparation\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer noopener\">casing layer video clip</a>.<br />RR","title":"Re: The Definitive \"Field Capacity\""}}